com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.controller

Class NavigationInputViewController

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.locuslabs.sdk.internal.maps.controller.NavigationInputViewController
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    BackStackItem

    public class NavigationInputViewController
extends java.lang.Object
implements BackStackItem
    Obtain a user's desired origin and destination for navigation. When the user input has been validated, this controller initiates the navigation.

    Opening the navigation input can be initiated from: -Directions button on map screen SearchViewController#showNavigationView() -Directions button on a POI (which could have been displayed from map screen or nav screen) SearchViewController#showNavigationView() -Tapping Back on navigation

    Closing the navigation input can result in: -Starting a navigation when user wants to navigate MapViewController.showNavigation(Position, Position) -Returning to map screen in the case of cancel

    This class's main data structure is the SearchResult. When other controllers feed data this controller, it converts the data into SearchResult. When this controller interacts with other controllers, e.g. NavigationViewController, it converts the SearchResult back into whatever data structure is needed by the other controller.

      • showNavigationInput

        public void showNavigationInput(boolean automaticallyAdvanceToDirectionsSummary)
        Primary point of entry for showing the navigation input screen.

        Callers can pre-populate the origin to be displayed to the user when the navigation input screen is displayed. Example is setting the Current Location by calling setDefaultOrigin(Position) or returning from the navigation screen to the navigation input screen, in which case setDefaultOrigin(POI) can be called.

        Callers can pre-populate a destination to be displayed to the user when the navigation input screen is displayed. Example is when the user tapped a POI and then tapped Directions to that POI. Another example is when the user returns from the navigation screen to the navigation input screen. In both cases, call setDefaultOrigin(POI).

        Parameters:
        automaticallyAdvanceToDirectionsSummary -

      • setCurrentLocation

        public void setCurrentLocation(Position currentPosition)
        When we obtain the user's position, update our record of the Current Location along with the Relevant Search results list. We remove Current Location (based on its name, a reserved word) from Recently Viewed.

        When we lose the user's position, remove the Current Location from the search results

        Be sure also to call setDefaultOrigin(Position) if the position update should result in showNavigationInput(boolean) to use the updated Current Location as the default origin.

        Parameters:
        currentPosition - the user's Position or null if position has been lost
